lly the name of the god of thunder in Norse mythology, Thor (Old Norse <i>Þórr</i>). It was not used as a personal name during the Middle Ages. The modern name is either a late 18th-century revival of the god's name or else a vernacular development of   Tord ."],"variants":[{"name":"Thor","meanings":["Originally the name of the god of thunder in Norse mythology, Thor (Old Norse <i>Þórr</i>). It was not used as a personal name during the Middle Ages. The modern name is either a late 18th-century revival of the god's name or else a vernacular development of   Tord ."]}]},{"name":"Matilda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Old German: Mighty battle maid"]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Amecia or Matilda had at least 1 son with Walter de Bayley."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","1272–1319":"1272–1319","1305–1371":"1305–1371","–Female":"Surnud","1305":"1305","about 1305":"umbes 1305","1371":"1371","1272":"1272","1319":"1319","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","1272–1319":"1272–1319","1305–1371":"1305–1371","–Female":"Kuollut","1305":"1305","about 1305":"noin 1305","1371":"1371","1272":"1272","1319":"1319","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England"},"fr":{"–":"Décédée","1272–1319":"1272–1319","1305–1371":"130